Vignette 3: Stitching

Overview 🔍

This vignette will walk you through the process of stitching together overlapping adjacent FOVs in your MERFISH experiment. Stitching is needed to obtain a coherent coordinate system across all FOVs. It can be done on DAPI images, or on the reference bit in MERFISH (i.e. the image that registration is performed with respect to – typically the first bit). Recall that as part of spotcalling (Chapter 3.3.2) and cell segmentation (Chapter 5.4), reference images are returned as REGIM_{ FOV Name }.png. We will be using the latter images and so stitching will have to be performed after the previous two tasks.

  1. Loading an example FOV and its surrounding Stitch images 🪡:

For stitching, we will need to load a reference FOV, and the FOVs immediately surrounding it. For instance, let’s select the same FOV processed in previous Chapters. From one of the GLOBALCOORD.csv files, we expect to load the four FOVs in blue below, alongside our reference FOV (red).

# load global information for current FOV
gcx <- data.table::fread( 
  list.files( params$parent_out_dir, pattern = 'GLOBALCOORD.csv', recursive = T, full.names = T )[1],
  data.table = F
)

# subset your coordinate data frame to a single sample (organoid)
prefixes <- sub("-.*", "", gcx$fov)
gcx <- gcx[which(prefixes == "MMStack_7"),] 
gcx <- gcx[!duplicated(gcx$fov),]
gcx$X <- as.integer( factor(gcx$x_microns) )
gcx$Y <- as.integer( factor(gcx$y_microns) )
gcx$CX <- gcx$X + 1i * gcx$Y # convert coordinates to complex numbers
gcx$fov_type <- ifelse(
  gcx$fov==params$current_fov, 'Reference',
  ifelse(
    Mod( gcx$CX - gcx$CX[gcx$fov==params$current_fov] ) == 1,
    'Neighbour', 'Other'))

gcx$short_name <- gsub('MMStack_|-Pos_|00', '', gcx$fov) # shorten the FOV names for visualization

ggplot( gcx ) +
  geom_text( aes(x=x_microns, y=y_microns, label=short_name, colour = fov_type),
             size = 5 ) +
  scale_colour_manual( name='', values = c('Reference' = 'red', 'Neighbour' = 'blue', 'Other' = 'black')) +
  scale_y_reverse() + xlab('X (microns)') + ylab('Y (microns)') +
  theme_minimal(base_size=14)

The actual loading is accomplished with the readImagesForStitch function.

The task of stitching is similar to image registration and our stitching algorithm stitchImages similarly relies on cross-correlation to a reference image. As default, the first image in the list – which should also be the current FOV being processed – is used.

stitchResults <- stitchImages(DapiList)
## Warning in stitchImages(DapiList): Z stack detected...Defaulting to MIP...

Stitching can be evaluated visually. Below we show how a FOV to the right of our reference FOV aligns prior to and after stitching.

## Subset a portion of the reference image and query image
refImage <- as.data.frame( imager::as.cimg( DapiList[[1]] ) ) #2_2
querImage <- as.data.frame( imager::as.cimg( DapiList[[2]] ) ) #2_1, top of 2_2
refImage$image <- names( DapiList )[1]
querImage$image <- names( DapiList )[2]

## Get corresponding shift vector
shiftVector <- stitchResults[stitchResults$fov == names(DapiList)[2], 'shift_pixel'] # get shift vector for the adjacent fov

## Visualise: Note the difference between stitched and unstitched are the values added to x,y
cowplot::plot_grid( plotlist = list(
  ggplot() +
    geom_raster( 
      data=refImage, 
      aes(x=x, y=y, alpha=value, fill = image), 
      ) +
    geom_raster( 
      data=querImage, 
      aes(x=x + 2960, y=y + 0, 
          alpha=value, fill = image)) +
    scale_fill_manual(name='', values=c('red', 'blue')) +
    scale_alpha_continuous( range = c(0.75, 0) ) +
    guides( alpha = 'none', fill = guide_legend(ncol=1) ) +
    scale_y_reverse() +
    theme_void( base_size= 14 ) +
    theme(legend.position = 'bottom') +
    coord_fixed() +
    ggtitle('Unstitched'),
  
  ggplot() +
    geom_raster( 
      data=refImage, 
      aes(x=x, y=y, alpha=value, fill = image), 
      ) +
    geom_raster( 
      data=querImage, 
      aes(x=x + Re(shiftVector), y=y + Im(shiftVector), 
          alpha=value, fill = image)) +
    scale_fill_manual(name='', values=c('red', 'blue')) +
    scale_alpha_continuous( range = c(0.75, 0) ) +
    guides( alpha = 'none', fill = guide_legend(ncol=1) ) +
    scale_y_reverse() +
    theme_void( base_size= 14 ) +
    theme(legend.position = 'bottom') +
    coord_fixed() +
    ggtitle('Stitched')
), nrow=1)

  1. Perform stitching on all FOVs 🧵:
## Preparation ahead of looping through FOVs
establishCleanSlate()
params$verbose <- F # does not work

## Start loop
for( fovName in params$fov_names ){
  
  ## Report current FOV / iteration 
  message( paste0(
    '\n', fovName, ': ', 
    which(params$fov_names==fovName), ' of ', 
    length(params$fov_names), '...' ) )
  
  ## Check if file has been created, skip if yes
  if( params$resumeMode ){
    checkFile <- file.exists( paste0(params$out_dir, 'STITCH/STITCH_', fovName, '.csv') )
    if(checkFile){
      cat('FOV has been processed...Skipping...')
      next
    }
  }
  
  ## Keep track of the current_fov
  params$current_fov <- fovName
  

  ## Stitch with respect to DAPI image
  imList <- readImagesForStitch( subDirectory = 'DAPI', loadProcessedImages =  T ) #Assume cell segmentation done
  stitchResults <- stitchImages( imList )
   if (nrow(stitchResults) == 0){
    print("skipping as this FOV does not have enough segmented cells.")
    next
   }
  
  ## Consolidate into a single dataframe
  colnames(stitchResults)[2] <- paste0('dapi_', colnames(stitchResults)[2])
  df <- stitchResults

  stitchResults[,colnames(df)[2]] <- df[match(stitchResults[,1], df[,1]),2]
  
  ## Save stitch dataframe
  saveStitch( stitchResults )
}

🎉 Congratulations! You have just finished stitching your MERFISH FOVs.
